<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Passes National Security Council Act </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2901183594 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2901183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Instead of devoting their Friday session to 
parliamentary control, on 28 January the National Assembly 
members engaged in regular legislative activity. 
  The Consultative National Security Council, as envisioned in 
the Bulgarian Constitution, finally was fully adopted at a 
second reading. Its functions were finally clarified at the 
National Assembly session. This will not only be an auxiliary 
organ of the president; the council will adopt no obligatory 
stands or proposals addressed at other institutions. 
  The clarification of the council's functions again posed the 
old disputed issue of its composition. This issue was discussed 
amid growing tension until the end of the session. According to 
the Constitution, the president of the Republic is chairman of 
the council. The prime minister, the four ministers most 
directly involved in security issues, the chief of the General 
Staff, the National Assembly chairman, and one representative 
from each parliamentary faction also are members of the council. 
No changes in this permanent composition were adopted, despite 
the fact that there were many new proposals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

