<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy: Attack on Serbs Would Mean War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101115994 Paris AFP in English 1142 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bijeljina, Bosnia, Jan 31 (AFP) -- Russian 
ultra-nationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy arrived on Monday 
in Bijeljina, northeastern Bosnia, for talks with leaders of the 
self-declared Bosnian Serb republic. 
  Some 2,000 to 3,000 people, many in uniform, were waiting to 
greet the rightwing Liberal Democratic Party leader, who is 
making a tour of parts of former Yugoslavia, including 
Serb-controlled regions of Croatia and Bosnia, an AFP 
correspondent said. 
  He was officially welcomed by the self-proclaimed president 
of the Serb Republic of Bosnia, Radovan Karadzic, Biljana 
Plavsic, from the collegial presidency and Aleksa Buha, a member 
of the government. Karadzic introduced Zhirinovskiy to a 
Russian volunteer fighting on the Tuzla front in northeast 
Bosnia. "The Russians have already arrived. They are coming on 
their own, it is a sign of Russia's goodwill," Zhirinovskiy said. 
  Zhirinovskiy was later scheduled to visit Vukovar in the 
self-proclaimed Serbian republic of Krajina in Croatia to meet 
the newly-elected self-styled president Milan Martic. 
  Zhirinovskiy warned on arrival in Belgrade on Sunday that 
airstrikes against the Serbs would be considered an attack by 
the west on Russia itself. 
  Attacks by NATO warplanes or UN troops on Serb positions 
anywhere in Bosnia or other areas of the former Yugoslavia 
"would be tantamount to a declaration of war on Russia," he 
said. "It's better that Europe not learn what retaliatory 
measurs we could take," he told a press conference. 
  He also called for UN troops to be pulled out of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and "let the Serbs settle the matter 
themselves." 
  Zhirinovskiy arrived here from Serbia after traveling 
through 
Hungary following a stormy tour of Slovenia, during which he was 
invited to leave by the government for causing a public 
disturbance and suggesting the independent republic should be 
reincorporated into rump Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

