<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR's Rose Meets With Mladic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3001182894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1720 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3001182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 30 Jan (TANJUG) -- General Michael Rose, 
UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] commander for former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Lieutenant General Ratko Mladic, 
commander of the army of the Srpska republic, had talks in Pale 
this afternoon. 
  After the meeting General Rose told journalists he was 
pleased with the meeting today. "The talks were interesting and 
related to an exchange of views on issues of interest to both 
sides," he said. 
  Speaking about the specific content of the talks today, 
General Mladic said: "General Rose presented vague claims in 
connection with some issues but they were clarified by the Serb 
side." 
  "I explained the same to General Briquemont. The rotation of 
UNPROFOR troops in Srebrenica falls within the competence of 
lower-ranking UNPROFOR commanders and it should not be blown up 
out of proportion, because that is precisely what Muslims and 
all those who are sponsoring them want in creating a smokescreen 
for the world public in order to conceal the Croat-Muslim war," 
Mladic said. 
  "As regards Tuzla airport, this is a concocted problem 
serving the same purpose, but the smokescreen is much thicker 
and bigger. There is no reason why we should haggle over this 
issue, as all the convoys can enter both Srebrenica and Tuzla as 
they please," Mladic said. 
  "However, Muslims have got bad advisers and think that we 
are 
naive and will easily swallow their bait. I informed General 
Rose about the fact that the Muslims and Croats declared war on 
the Serb people. Let them take it back; it will be easy to find 
a speedy agreement on everything, including Tuzla. There are 
also airports on Serb territory. Serbs cannot even receive 
vaccines for babies while the Muslims can even seek to control 
all international airports. We will talk about this with the 
warring sides," Mladic said. 
  "We have never had any conflicts with UNPROFOR commanders, 
nor with any generals, because it was not the United Nations 
that declared war on us, but Tudjman and Izetbegovic," the Serb 
commander concluded. 

</TEXT>

