<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Herceg-Bosna Denies Presence of Croatian Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901235394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2100 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901235394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The political department of the Defense Ministry of 
the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna has issued a statement in 
response to a letter to UN Security Council Chairman Karel 
Kovanda by Muslim Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic, in which he 
accused the Republic of Croatia of allegedly sending its regular 
units to take part in military actions in the territory of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Silajdzic's letter is completely unfounded, 
and it is yet another attempt to turn the attention of the 
international public away from the true problem, which is the 
Muslim army's continued aggression against the Croat people in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Muslims' persistence in continuing 
the war. This is the gist of the statement. 
  We declare that there are no regular units of the Croatian 
Army in the territory of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna, and 
that the political leadership of Herceg-Bosna has never asked 
the Croatian Army and leaders to send Croatian Army units to 
Herceg-Bosna. 
  It is true that the authorities of the Croat republic of 
Herceg-Bosna have sent a call-up to all able-bodied citizens of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina of Croat nationality -- including members of 
the Croatian Army born in Bosnia-Herzegovina who volunteered for 
the Croatian Army at the beginning of the aggression against 
Croatia -- to join HVO [Croatian Defense Council] units in the 
defense of their people and their historic areas. Before 
joining HVO units, all volunteers from the Croatian Army born in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina were demobilized from the Croatian Army; that 
is, they left its ranks. The truth is only that HVO units are 
much better manned due to a good turnout of citizens of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina of Croat nationality who stayed in Croatia, 
the statement says. 

</TEXT>

