<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ICRC Officials Visit Serb Doctors in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901204094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1907 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2901204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 29 (TANJUG) -- Officials of the 
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) on January 23 
visited five Serb doctors and three nurses held by the Moslems 
in Sarajevo for allegedly attempting to flee a Moslem quarter of 
the city. 
  The ICRC said in a letter to the Health Ministry of the 
Bosnian Serb Republic on Saturday that the arrested medical 
workers were allowed to contact their families through the ICRC. 
  Health Minister Dragan Kalinic on Saturday sent a letter to 
the coordinator for medical evacuations of the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees threatening to suspend cooperation in 
response to this inhumane and criminal act. The health 
authorities of the Bosnian Serb republic will suspend all 
medical evacuations until the arrested doctors and nurses have 
been uncondtionally released and allowed to freely enter Serb 
territory, said Kalinic. 
  Speaker of the Bosnian Serb Parliament Momcilo Krajisnik and 
Bosnian Moslem Premier Haris Silajdzic met at Sarajevo Airport 
on Sunday [as received] afternoon for talks on rebuilding 
confidence among the warring sides and releasing the Serb 
doctors and nurses from the central Moslem prison in Sarajevo. 
  Until they were arrested, the doctors and nurses worked in 
Moslem-controlled hospitals in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

