<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungary's Jeszenszky Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sanctions Discussed With Kontic </H4>
<F P=102> LD2801152994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1405 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2801152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 28 Jan (TANJUG)--It is with pleasure that 
Hungary will uphold the lifting of the sanctions adversely 
affecting not only the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia but 
Hungary as well, Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky told 
FRY Prime Minister Radoje Kontic today. Federal Prime Minister 
Kontic received the Hungarian foreign minister at the Palace of 
the Federation today. The meeting was also attended by Federal 
Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic. 
  Views were exchanged on bilateral relations between the FRY 
and Hungary, stability in the Balkans, and the consequences of 
the unjustly imposed sanctions. The two sides expressed mutual 
interest in the development of good-neighborly relations and the 
desire to resolve all disputes through dialogue. 
  "Yugoslavia is firmly determined to settle all disputed 
issues in a peaceful way", the Yugoslav prime minister pointed 
out. The prime minister also stressed that relations with 
neighbors were a priority in Yugoslavia's foreign policy, 
emphasizing that national minorities should be bridges of 
cooperation, not causes for confrontation. Consequently, all 
national minorities in the FRY -- including members of the 
Hungarian minority -- are enjoying and will continue to enjoy 
all rights in conformity with the highest international 
standards, Kontic stressed. He informed Minister Jeszenszky 
about the effects of the unjustly imposed sanctions and said 
there were no longer any reasons for maintaining them. 
  Hungarian Foreign Minister Jeszenszky conveyed his 
government's interest in maintaining good-neighborly relations 
with the FRY and expressed his conviction that they will be even 
more beneficial in the future. Jeszenszky believes that peace 
in former Bosnia-Herzegovina was now closer at hand than ever 
before and assessed that the FRY was making a significant 
contribution to this effect. 
  The two sides also discussed economic cooperation, 
especially 
after the sanctions. 
  Prime Minister Kontic extended an invitation to the 
Hungarian 
prime minister to visit Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50402 </DOCNO>
