<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Socialists Reject Compromise With Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901204194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1756 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901204194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 29 Jan -- Vuk Draskovic, chairman of the 
Serbian Renewal Movement told Radio Jagodina today that during 
three-hour long talks last night between representatives of the 
parliamentary opposition parties and the Socialist Party of 
Serbia [SPS], Depos [Democratic Movement of Serbia] offered to 
support the formation of a minority Socialist government in 
exchange for the position of the [Serbian] Assembly speaker. 
  However, according to Draskovic, no agreement was reached 
because the Socialists "rejected a compromise". Depos, as the 
leading parliamentary opposition party offered the SPS a 
compromise to the effect that a deputy of the democratic 
opposition of Serbia be appointed Assembly speaker, and in 
return it would give up not only the post of prime minister, but 
also all government ministries. As a sign of good will we 
offered to have two deputy speakers in the Assembly presidency. 
To reject the readiness of the largest opposition party to 
support the formation of a minority Socialist government in the 
name of national unity, while in exchange it would obtain only 
the post of the first among the equal in the Serbian Assembly, 
is the proof of the Socialists' utmost intolerance," Draskovic 
said. 

</TEXT>

