<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Party Favors Opposition Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3001172094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU3001172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Srdjan Savic] </F>
  [Excerpt] The process of internal party discussions on 
policy concepts and personal issues ended at the extraordinary 
convention of the Democratic Party without the party 
experiencing a rift. This was stated by Zoran Djindjic, who 
replaced Dragoljub Micunovic as president of the Democratic 
Party last night, at his first news conference in this capacity. 
Srdjan Savic reports: 
  [Savic] Yesterday's discussion on various policy concepts 
was not a discussion on the party's program orientations, which 
means that the Democratic Party will continue the policy that 
existed before the election. This was stated by the new leader 
of the Democratic Party, Zoran Djindjic. He stressed that the 
former party president Dragoljub Micunovic would remain the head 
of the deputies' caucus in the federal parliament and that his 
full participation in the work of the party would be appreciated. 
  Speaking about the continuation of the talks on the 
inauguration of the republican assembly scheduled for tomorrow 
[31 January], Djindjic stressed that the opposition expects a 
gesture of goodwill from the ruling party. This means that the 
opposition expects the ruling party to allow Depos [Democratic 
Movement of Serbia] to appoint the chairman of the assembly. 
However, the Democratic Party will try its utmost to unblock 
the work of the Serbian Assembly even at the price of a 
non-opposition assembly chairman, because it wants to enable the 
parliament to perform its main, legislative function, Zoran 
Djindjic said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

