<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olechowski Back From U.S.; Views `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901180994 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1600 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by Warsaw TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Affairs Minister Andrzej Olechowski has 
returned from the United States, where he held talks with 
representatives of the U.S. Government on the Partnership for 
Peace program, among other things. According to the minister, 
the results of the talks will bring Poland closer to 
participation in the implementation of the program. 
  [Begin Olechowski recording] The primary objective of the 
Partnership for Peace concept is to create a Europe without 
borders and dividing lines. If, however, dividing lines were to 
exist, it is understood--and this view is shared--that Poland 
would find itself on the NATO side of the divide. Because the 
United States firmly emphasizes that its security depends on our 
security, it is in the interest of both sides, Poland and the 
United States--and NATO--that Poland should become an active 
partner in the Partnership for Peace. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

