<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Handling of Dismissal `Peculiar' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3101112194 Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA in Polish 29-30 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> WS3101112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Untitled commentary by Bozena Wawrzewska under the </F>
"Commentaries" rubric] 
  [Text] Yesterday, the government displayed some peculiar 
behavior which was watched by all of society. 
  The prime minister dismissed Deputy Finance Minister 
Kawalec, 
about which Mr. Kawalec learned from the radio. The superior of 
the dismissed minister--Marek Borowski, finance minister and 
deputy prime minister--whose motion would be needed to bring 
about a dismissal like this, addressed a question to the prime 
minister on the reasons behind the dismissal. In reply, PAP 
received a communique issued by the Government's Press Office to 
the effect that Deputy Finance Minister Kawalec's dismissal is 
not linked to the privatization of Bank Slaski, whereas the real 
reasons were not given either to the press or to Deputy Prime 
Minister Borowski. All the prime minister's press secretary had 
to say is that there he has no comment on the issue. 
  Politics require the courage to tell the truth directly, 
even 
when it is about decisions which were hard to make. The prime 
minister has asked the press to report honestly, but what he is 
doing now is condemning journalists for speculating and 
expressing views on what could be described as a weird style of 
governing, to put it mildly. 
  So, faced with deficiencies in the government's information 
policies and with a lack of explanations which the public 
expects, one is entitled to draw different kinds of conclusions 
on, for instance, possible frictions within the coalition, a 
battle between the Polish Peasant Party and the Democratic Left 
Alliance, mutual disloyalties among different cabinet members 
who talk to one another through journalists, who--as they often 
stress--they distrust, or about facing coalition partners with 
accomplished facts, which is not the first time this has 
happened. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

