<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Denies Ties to Gunrunning From El Salvador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3112223093 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1601 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> PA3112223093 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 31 Dec (ACAN-EFE) -- The Guatemalan 
Army denied today that Guatemalan military personnel have ties 
with the gunrunning activities from El Salvador, as has been 
reported by a leader of the former guerrilla Farabundo Marti 
National Liberation Front (FMLN). Major Edith Vargas, spokesman 
for the Information and Press Department of the Army (DIDE), 
asserted that the Guatemalan Armed Forces obtain their weapons 
"legally" and not clandestinely. 
  Eduardo Linares, former guerrilla and now a political leader 
of the FMLN, accused, in statements to the Guatemala City PRENSA 
LIBRE newspaper, the Guatemalan military institution of being 
primarily responsible for the gunrunning activities. According 
to Linares, on one occasion the FMLN had bought an arsenal from 
Guatemalan military personnel. However, Major Vargas asserted 
that the former guerrilla "is totally misinformed." 
  The Guatemalan Army has charged the FMLN of gunrunning for 
the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG). 
Furthermore, Deputy Government Minister Adolfo Reyes accused 
the FMLN of being involved in criminal activities in that 
Central American country and said "we have evidence" to this 
effect. Recently, Guatemalan Interior Minister Arnoldo Ortiz 
and Defense Minister General Mario Enriquez said they suspected 
former FMLN members were involved in the abductions that are 
occurring in Guatemala to collect ransoms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

