<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Politicians, ARI Member Agree Not To Renegotiate U.S. Bases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0201231794 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 2 
Jan 93 p 1A </F>

<F P=103> PA0201231794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esperanza Navarro Francois] </F>
  [Text] A leading member of the Interoceanic Region 
Authority (ARI) and several presidential candidates agreed that 
now is not the time to negotiate the presence of military bases 
in Panama. 
  Mariano Mena, general secretary of the General Confederation 
of Panamanian Workers (CGTP) and a member of ARI, told LA 
ESTRELLA DE PANAMA that the Torrijos-Carter Treaties must be 
fulfilled. The country is in no condition to negotiate the 
military bases. 
  According to the leader, the proximity of the election and 
the political situation do not offer the appropriate conditions 
for modifying the treaty. 
  According to the Southern Command Treaty Implementation 
Office, 9,000 U.S. soldiers and 2,562 civilians work at the U.S. 
bases in Panama along with 5,718 Panamanian civilian employees. 
  David Guerra, presidential candidate for the National Unity 
Mission party (MUN), said Panama has more immediate needs to 
attend to, and modifying the Torrijos Carter Treaty would just 
create more problems. 
  Tomas Herrera, presidential candidate for the Civic Renewal 
Party, said he agrees with former President Jimmy Carter that 
the bases will disappear within the time established by the 
treaty. 
  He indicated that the new government could negotiate the 
treaties responsibly, seeking to increase Panama's income. 
  Herrera pointed out that "Panama could benefit by 
renegotiating the U.S. military bases as Italy, Germany, the 
United Kingdom, Turkey, and Korea have." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

