<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamber President Favors National Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL3012211593 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1700 
GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> FL3012211593 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The president of the Chamber of Deputies is 
opposed to the project of an international conference in Miami, 
proposed by President Aristide last week. He also is convinced 
that this project is not a winner for his other colleague 
deputies. Let us listen to Mr. Antoine Joseph at Edner Jean's 
microphone: 
  [Begin Joseph recording in Creole] I encourage all ideas 
that 
allow Haitians to sit together and discuss, whether it is at an 
international or national conference. However, I think that the 
political parties in the Parliament should give their opinion on 
the idea of the national conference, as the invitation was sent 
to them. If they reject it, then the idea will fail. Right now, 
many political parties favor the national conference. Some of 
them have said no. As I had already supported the national 
conference, I still support it. This is because I think it can 
embrace more subjects than an international conference. Many 
people think that the Haitian crisis must be repatriated, and I 
am not totally against that idea. Let me remind you that the 
Washington protocol agreement was signed between the 
international community and partly the Parliament. Although two 
Haitians signed the Governors Island Accord, it was with the 
mediation of the international community. What would be better 
is to have the international community broaden the framework of 
the negotiations and the search for a solution by inviting 
several sectors-- such as political parties, the labor unions, 
the peasant organizations, the active sectors of national life, 
and the social professional associations. All those people 
should sit together in order to find a solution. [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

