<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Links Between Rebels, Clerics Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0201162294 Paris AFP in Spanish 1145 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0201162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, Mexico, 2 Jan (AFP) -- An official 
communique issued today said the government of the Mexican State 
of Chiapas "has insisted unsuccessfully on its proposal to hold 
a dialogue" with the Zapata National Liberation Army (EZLN), 
which took by storm the mayor's offices in five municipalities. 
  The communique emphasized that the authorities have 
requested 
the EZLN members, who issued a "Declaration of War" against the 
Army and the Mexican Government on Saturday, to "put aside their 
violent and belligerent position against the civilian population 
and the municipal authorities." 
  A day after the sudden attack by several hundred guerrillas 
on the Chiapas municipalities of San Cristobal de las Casas, 
Ocosingo, Altamirano, Las Margaritas, and Chanal, the government 
said, it is "concerned about the prevailing atmosphere in the 
municipal county seats," which remained occupied by the EZLN. 
  At first, authorities indicated that the wave of violence 
had 
been unleashed by 200 Indian peasants, but their most recent 
communique claims that the peasant groups "are infiltrated by 
people with obvious paramilitary training." The communique 
added that the infiltrators have "high-powered weapons, wear 
green pants, khaki shirts, and red and black badges, and present 
themselves as an organization of presumed liberation forces." 
  The communique pointed out that residents of the occupied 
municipalities "have said that some Catholic priests and deacons 
who uphold liberation theology have become involved with these 
groups and are supporting them with the radio communications 
system of the San Cristobal Diocese." 
  It noted: "The so-called Emiliano Zapata organization is 
linked to the Revolutionary Workers Clandestine People's Union 
Party and to the Poor People's Party (guerrillas), and it has 
forced the Ocisingo radio station to broadcast harangues calling 
for violence." 
  The government's communique pointed out that Felipe Arriaga, 
the bishop of Tuxtla Gutierrez, "has urged these groups to put 
aside their violent position and regretted that priests and 
deacons are accused of involvement in these incidents." 
  In Mexico City, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the presidential 
candidate of the center-leftist Party of the Democratic 
Revolution, said in a news release that "violence, whatever its 
origin, only leads to bloodshed, destruction, and greater social 
backwardness," adding that the government's duty is to inform 
people about the true situation in Chiapas. 
  According to NOTIMEX -- the official news agency -- 
Government Under Secretary Ricardo Garcia said the Mexican 
Government is urging peasants in Chiapas to be reasonable and to 
try to resolve their problems within a legal framework. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50466 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat001_c_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0201170094 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1512 
GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0201170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The most important event featured today in Mexico 
City's newspapers is the following: An armed group, mostly 
Indians, the self-styled Zapata National Liberation Army [EZLN] 
-- linked with the Procup [Revolutionary Workers Clandestine 
People's Union Party] and the Poor People's Party, according to 
state officials -- violently seized on the morning of 1 January 
the municipal offices in San Cristobal de las Casas, Ocosingo, 
Altamirano, Chanal, and Las Margaritas, with a toll of at least 
11 dead and dozens of injured -- three in clashes sustained with 
public forces -- according to unofficial sources. 
  According reports from state officials, the Indians -- 
according to witnesses, there were about 2,200 of them -- were 
armed with AR-15 rifles, .22 caliber rifles, and shotguns, and 
they simultaneously stormed the five municipalities. Given the 
situation, the government secretariat warned it cannot justify 
the fact that fair social demands, for which there exists a 
willingness to provide a solution, be used as a pretext to 
violate legal order. 
  A Government Ministry communique said the government is 
urging these groups to act wisely, recant, and establish 
negotiations within a legal framework. Meanwhile, state 
officials called these actions a violent provocation. They also 
ordered public security forces to dissuade the armed groups, 
making it possible to seek a solution to their demands, which 
have yet to be stated, through dialogue and legal means. 
  Given the situation, the bishops of Chiapas State issued an 
appeal to the EZLN forces to accept the bishops' mediation in an 
effort to restore harmony and social tranquility in the 
municipalities involved in the conflict. Furthermore, it is 
appropriate to mention that contacts are being maintained 
between federal government officials and state officials in an 
effort to quickly resolve the situation. 
  The declaration of war issued by the Sandinist National 
Liberation Army, excuse me, the EZLN, to the Mexican Federal 
Army asks the nation's legislative and judicial branches to 
strive to restore the nation's legality and stability. The EZLN 
is asking international organizations and the International Red 
Cross to supervise and regulate the clashes that its forces are 
waging to protect the civilian population. 
  The declaration of war rejects any links to drug 
traffickers, 
narcoguerrillas, or any other groups when referring to the 
struggle waged by the EZLN, which has ordered its military 
forces to advance toward the country's capital, defeat the 
Mexican Federal Army, and allow the liberated people to 
democratically elect their own administrative authorities. 
  This is, in short, what is currently taking place in five 
municipalities in Chiapas State -- San Cristobal de las Casas, 
Ocosingo, Altamirano, Chanal, and Las Margaritas -- where the 
self- proclaimed EZLN violently seized the municipal offices and 
where there is a toll of 11 dead and dozens wounded. 
  A report issued early this morning by NOTIMEX reports that, 
after stating the need to contribute their efforts to prevent a 
possible confrontation involving the people of Chiapas, the 
bishops of Chiapas agreed to take part as mediators to restore 
harmony and peace in the municipalities involved in the conflict. 
  A communique issued by the diocese of Tuxtla Gutierrez and 
Tapachula, Chiapas State, stated that, in an effort to create 
conditions that will allow a fruitful dialogue, we issue an 
appeal to the so-called EZLN, urging it to accept four points. 
The bishops request an end to violence, respect for people's 
lives, the release of kidnapped people, and they urge them to 
put down their weapons, respect the law and human rights, and to 
take part in a dialogue to resolve social problems. 
  The bishops' document mentions that, in the event that their 
proposal is accepted, within the next 48 hours the bishops 
promise to ask the government to establish an office to handle 
social problems in the region. The bishops said they have been 
trying to contact the bishop of San Cristobal de las Casas, 
Samuel Ruiz Garcia, since early this morning. Their efforts 
have failed so far, but they add they can count on the 
solidarity of this diocese's pastor. 
  The bishops of Chiapas note that their agreement to serve as 
mediators was prompted by requests they received from different 
social groups in Chiapas to search for a solution to the 
problems that have arisen in San Cristobal de las Casas, 
Ocosingo, Las Margaritas, and Altamirano. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

