<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Raul Castro Congratulates People, Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL3112154093 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1255 
GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> FL3112154093 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Last night [30 December] at the Ministry of the 
Revolutionary Armed Forces headquarters, Raul and Commander of 
the Revolution Juan Almeida presented epaulets to a group of 
Revolutionary Armed Forces [FAR] officers promoted to the rank 
of colonel, men who have fulfilled their mission exemplarily in 
defense, teaching, and research. 
  After the ceremony, I approached Army General Raul Castro 
and 
asked him to speak to the Cuban people. Please listen to his 
words. I invite our listeners to keep them in mind. 
  [Begin recording] To our entire people, especially to my FAR 
and Interior Ministry [Minint] comrades: I congratulate you on 
the 35th anniversary of the triumph of the Revolution. This 
congratulations is for struggle against all problems. The coming 
year will also be difficult. Everything is dependent upon our 
effort. 
  To the FAR and Minint troops: We have faced difficult times 
before, even before the triumph of the Revolution; even earlier 
generations, beginning with the Mambises. We maintain that same 
spirit of never surrendering, of courageously facing all 
adversity -- objective and subjective problems. There are as 
many of one as of the other. 
  This year, during the 35th anniversary, when television and 
radio play the national anthem -- which, as a matter of fact, 
they forgot to play a year or two ago -- please dedicate at 
least one moment to thinking about, internalizing thoughts: What 
has each one of us done? Not what have others done. What are our 
faults? What individual shortcomings have we? Begin with 
yourself and follow up with an analysis of the whole the Cuban 
people. 
  I wish you happiness, which means: Continue the struggle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

