<H3> <TI>   Raul Castro Attends FAR Promotion Ceremony </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0301024294 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0301024294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On the occasion of the 35th anniversary of the 
triumph of the Revolution, 33 Revolutionary Armed Forces [FAR] 
officers were promoted to colonel and ship captain. The 
ceremony was presided over by FAR Minister Army General Raul 
Castro. 
  Army Gen. Raul Castro and Commander of the Revolution Juan 
Almeida, president of the Cuban Revolution Veterans Association 
[ACRC], presented the promotions. Officer Rene Corredera Brito, 
an internationalist pilot who has received the Antonio Maceo 
Medal of Valor, spoke on behalf of the officers who were 
promoted. He thanked everyone for the trust placed in them and 
for the promotion they received, which is a sign of recognition 
for their work. Brito reiterated the officers support for the 
cause of the defense of the fatherland and their loyalty to the 
commander in chief, whose example a FAR officer should follow, 
always ready to confront the enemy and always filled with the 
belief that our noble ideals of national independence and 
socialism will triumph. 
  Division General Nestor Lopez Cuba, chief of the FAR 
political directorate, closed the event with a dynamic speech. 
Div. Gen. Lopez Cuba described 1993 as the most difficult year 
since the triumph of the Revolution, and he described the 
special period as a hard test that the patriots and 
revolutionaries are confronting with courage, loyalty, and the 
belief that it is possible to resist and win. Lopez Cuba told 
the officers that: We have absolute trust in you because we 
know you will be worthy bearers of the title of colonel of the 
Armed Forces founded by our invincible commander in chief, Fidel 
Castro, 37 years ago. He will continue to lead us, as always, 
through the most difficult and glorious moments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

