<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bishop Denies Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0301204294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1916 
GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0301204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Live report by Jose Luis Sarmiento Avila] </F>
  [Text] Bishop Felipe Arizmendi, bishop of Tapachula, 
Chiapas State, has emphasized in an exclusive interview that the 
Church has nothing to do with the armed rebellion. Quite the 
contrary, he said, the Church offers to act as mediator to reach 
a consensus and prevent useless bloodshed. 
  The prelate explained that the recent events are a desperate 
measure in the face of the poverty and deprivation in which the 
Indians are immersed, above all in the Lacandon zone. 
  Bishop Felipe Arizmendi warned that any violence in Chiapas 
will result in worse repression of the Indians. He said the 
important thing is to know who is behind the Zapatista army and 
to learn if they are acting in favor of private interests that 
do not include the Indian population. 
  The Catholic Church in Chiapas has reiterated its appeal 
that 
political wisdom and historical responsibility motivate the 
parties to the conflict to seek an honest and responsible 
dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

