<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bishops Reaffirm Willingness To Mediate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401025694 Mexico City Radio Acir Network in Spanish 0056 
GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0401025694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio Acir Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maricarmen Camacho from Tuxtla Gutierrez] </F>
  [Text] The bishops of the three dioceses of Chiapas 
State--namely, Felipe Arismendi Esquivel of Tapachula, Samuel 
Ruiz Garcia of San Cristobal de las Casas, and Felipe Aguirre 
Franco of Tuxtla Gutierrez--have reaffirmed their willingness to 
mediate between the armed groups and representatives of the 
Mexican Government to establish a dialogue and find a solution 
to the conflict in the Chiapas State highlands. 
  During a news conference San Cristobal Bishop Samuel Ruiz 
Garcia said that they are awaiting a positive reply from 
subversive groups to the start of negotiations and an end to the 
armed confrontations. 
  [Begin Ruiz recording] We proposed contributing our 
recognized moral influence; all three of us agree with that 
service proposal. The mediation process will depend on the 
parties' behavior. We hope to be able to reach the party that 
declared war to find out whether it accepts our mediation. 
  What follows? We do not know, because that depends on the 
circumstances. All we can do is voice our willingness to serve 
as mediators. We will not hold talks with them, only serve as 
mediators of a dialogue. [end recording] 
  The three bishops said they deeply regret the developments 
at 
the start of 1994. Deputy Government Secretary Ricardo Garcia 
Villalobos has reported that the Mexican Government is willing 
to hold talks with representatives of the subversive groups to 
settle this problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

