<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Reinforce Troops by 6,000 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401002994 Paris AFP in Spanish 2341 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401002994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 3 Jan (AFP) -- The Mexican Army has 
12,000 soldiers who are "trying to repel the uprising" of 
Indians of the Zapata National Liberation Army (EZLN), initiated 
on 1 January in the southern State of Chiapas, the newspaper 
ULTIMAS NOTICIAS reported this Monday. 
  The Armed Forces have reinforced their troops with 6,000 
soldiers in the area of conflict, where there were already a 
number of soldiers prior to the EZLN-launched offensive, the 
newspaper stated, not citing its sources. 
  This report has not yet been officially confirmed. 
  According to Chiapas authorities, the guerrillas "are just a 
few," possibly some 400, but estimates made by journalists who 
have traveled to the region list the EZLN members at between 800 
and 1,000. 
  A guerrilla has told the press that his troops consist of 
approximately 5,000 men. 
  The area of conflict is located approximately 700 km south 
of 
Mexico City. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50555 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat002_c_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

