<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rebels Maintaining Presence in at Least 5 Towns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401021294 Paris AFP in Spanish 0108 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas, Mexico, 3 Jan (AFP) -- 
According to various sources, the Zapata National Liberation 
Army (EZLN) is maintaining a guerrilla presence today in at 
least five towns of the southern State of Chiapas, leaving four 
mayors offices violently occupied in the past few days. 
  Rafael Gonzalez Lastra, the Chiapas Government secretary 
general, has told a news conference that the EZLN "aggressors" 
left the mayors offices in Las Margaritas and Chanal today and 
that Mexican Army troops are in the city of Comitan, south of 
San Cristobal, to guarantee peace. 
  The EZLN forces violently seized the mayors offices in San 
Cristobal de las Casas, Las Margaritas, Chanal, Altamirano, and 
Ocosingo on 1 January in what constituted a violent guerrilla 
outbreak. 
  The guerrillas left San Cristobal on 2 January and moved 
toward Rancho Nuevo, where they have sustained several clashes 
with the troops stationed at the 31st Military Zone Garrison. 
  The EZLN presence continues in Ocosingo, where there have 
been clashes, and Altamirano, Oxchuch, Huiztan, and Cuxulja, 
which they occupied on Sunday. 
  Certain reports stated that a group of rebels has taken over 
Guadalupe Tepeyac, in Las Margaritas Municipality. 
  Gonzalez Lastra said he trusts that order will be 
reestablished in Ocosingo and Altamirano "within the next few 
hours." 
  Media reports, which authorities have not confirmed, state 
that the troops arrested 12 civilians in Comitan. Near the city 
an EZLN unit kidnapped former Chiapas Governor Absalon 
Castellanos on Sunday. His whereabouts are unknown. 

</TEXT>

