<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Retake Town </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401041994 Paris AFP in Spanish 0345 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401041994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 3 Jan (AFP) -- A government source has 
reported that the Mexican Armed Forces retook control of the 
town of Ocosingo in southern Chiapas State this afternoon. It 
had been under the control of Zapata National Liberation Army 
(EZLN) guerrillas since 1 January. 
  Chiapas Government Under Secretary Julio Cesar Cancino has 
told television media that Altamirano is the only town in the 
hands of the "criminals" (guerrillas). The official did not 
provide details on the recovery of Ocosingo or the number of 
Army and rebel casualties during more than 24 hours of fighting. 
  The authorities have only admitted the presence of EZLN 
rebels in four municipal capitals (San Cristobal, Ocosingo, Las 
Margaritas, and Altamirano). Meanwhile, media sources has 
reported there was guerrilla presence in five other towns: 
Chanal, Oxchuc, Huiztan, Cuxulja, and Rancho Nuevo. Cancino 
said that the Mexican Army is protecting the highways leading to 
Tuxtla Gutierrez, the capital of Chiapas, where "many rumors" 
have been heard about the activities of EZLN members. 
  He stressed the possibility that the strife-torn situation 
in 
Chiapas as a result of the violent appearance of the EZLN will 
end 4 January. 

</TEXT>

