<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Two Hundred Said Killed, 500 Wounded </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401062394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0539 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez (Mexico), 4 Jan (EFE) -- The Armed 
Forces have recovered four towns that had been occupied by the 
Zapata National Liberation Army (EZLN) after 48 hours of clashes 
and skirmishes that unofficially have left almost 200 people 
dead and 500 injured. 
  The rebels left their positions in Oxchuc and Las 
Margaritas, 
while the Mexican Army expelled them from San Cristobal and 
Oconsingo, in northern and northeastern Chiapas State. 
  Sources close to the Chiapas government have told EFE that 
it 
can be said unofficially that 200 people were killed, including 
rebels, civilians, and soldiers, and 500 were wounded during the 
past three days of conflict since the EZLN attacked several 
towns in Chiapas. 
  They added that 25 rebels were captured during the military 
operations and that apparently one of them is "Commander 
Marcos," who appeared in a picture talking to the press at the 
San Cristobal mayor's office, which was reproduced by Mexican 
newspapers. 

</TEXT>

