<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401211594 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401211594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 3 
January. Source is cited in parentheses following each item. 
  Rodolfo Uribe, director of the National Administrative 
Department of Statistic (DANE) has disclosed that inflation in 
Colombia during 1993 had reached 22.6 percent, 2.5 points less 
that in 1992. He indicated that despite the government's 
inability to reach its 22 percent inflation goal, it came pretty 
close, evidence that "it is winning the battle against 
inflation." Uribe recalled that in 1993 accumulated inflation 
in Colombia reached 25.13 percent. In December 1993, cost of 
living increased most in Cali at 1.67 percent, followed closely 
by Medellin with 1.46 percent. Santa Fe de Bogota recorded 
inflation of 1.03 percent in December. Colombian cities with 
the lowest increase in cost of living were Cucuta with 0.85 
percent and Pasto with 0.15 percent. President Cesar Gaviria's 
administration has set 19 percent as the 1994 inflation goal. 
(Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1752 GMT 2 Jan 94) 
  Figures made public today by DANE reveal that unemployment 
fell during 1993 from 9.6 percent to 7.9 percent. According to 
DANE figures, unemployment levels in the four leading 
metropolitan areas of Santa Fe de Bogota, Cali, Medellin, and 
Barranquilla were less than 7.6 percent. The report also 
reveals that the private sector created at least 75,000 jobs in 
the past year. Unemployment in the four leading metropolitan 
areas during December totalled approximately 354,000, of an 
economically active labor market of 4.7 million Colombians. 
(Madrid EFE in Spanish 2041 GMT 28 Dec 93) 
  Gasoline prices were adjusted by 19 percent throughout 
Colombia on 27 December. The price of regular gasoline 
increased from 578 to 688 pesos, and premium gasoline prices 
increased from 718 to 854 pesos. Cocinol, fuel distributed 
mainly in Santa Fe de Bogota's lower income communities, rose 
from 85 to 100 pesos, or 17.65 percent. It is the first time in 
six years that the government has increased gasoline prices 
based on the 1994 inflation goal of 19 percent. Previously, 
price adjustments were implemented with the intention of 
covering fluctuations in the cost of living index during the 
current year. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 20 Dec 
93 pp 1a, 8a) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

