<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Might Travel to Mexico To Help Solve Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501002694 Paris AFP in Spanish 1923 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501002694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 4 Jan (AFP) -- Salvadoran President 
Alfredo Cristiani said today he will travel to Mexico to offer 
the Mexican Government "cooperation" to solve the crisis there 
after armed clashes broke out in that country over the weekend. 
  "We are willing to cooperate with the Mexican Government in 
whatever it believes we can cooperate," Cristiani told a news 
conference. The Salvadoran president asked today the 
Legislative Assembly for permission to leave the country, and 
according to the president, he "might" go to Mexico this weekend. 
  Cristiani said that he was "disappointed" by the outbreak of 
clashes between the Mexican Armed Forces and the so-called 
Zapatista National Liberation Army (EZLN), which supports 
demands of the very poor Indian population in Chiapas State, on 
the border with Guatemala. 
  Along with Spain, Colombia, and Venezuela, Mexico forms part 
of the "group of friendly countries" which supported the 
negotiations between the Cristiani government and the former 
rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which 
in 1992 ended a 12-year-old civil war in El Salvador. 

</TEXT>

