<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 3 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0301220394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0301220394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Salvadoran economic developments monitored through 3 
January 1994. Source is cited in parentheses following each item. 
  The Economy Ministry reported the following figures for 
1993: 

  -  Inflation was 12.1 percent (government goal: 12 
percent). 
  -  GNP increased 5 percent (last year's total was 4.6 
percent). 
  -  Fiscal deficit was 1.8 percent of GNP. 
  -  Exports equaled 
$600 million. Despite a drop in coffee prices, exports 
increased 22 percent, and exports of assembled goods increased 
39 percent. 
  -  Net international reserves were $663 
million. 
  -  Increase in formal employment, according to Social 
Security affiliation, was 13 percent. 
  Economy Minister Enrique Cordova believes that 1994 could 
see 
an economic upswing in El Salvador but warned that "economic 
growth must be maintained until the year 2000 to recover 
pre-1978 levels." (San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 29 
Dec 93 p 3) 
  The 1992-93 coffee harvest reached 3.3 million quintals, 
while the 1993-94 crop is expected to reach 2 million quintals. 
Some of the reasons for the reduced production is the 
development of new neighborhoods on land previously used for 
growing coffee, the lack of adequate attention to coffee 
plantations, and the 20 percent export retention in force since 
October to improve prices. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1935 
GMT 30 Dec 93) 

</TEXT>

