<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Justice Poppe Calls President `a Gringo Made in Bolivia' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0401181394 La Paz Radio Fides Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0401181394 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Radio Fides Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Potosi] </F>
  [Text] Justice Ernesto Poppe Zubieta yesterday said during 
a news conference: They could not find any evidence against me 
in either the Ibarra or the Meco Domingez case. The United 
States is interested in having me removed from office because I 
demanded to know where the property and assets seized from drug 
traffickers ended up. I was against Supreme Decree 21060 
because it was inhuman. I rejected Article 55 of that law, 
which supported private businessmen, enabling them to hire 
workers without due regard for their rights. 
  I am a genuine member of the MNR [Nationalist Revolutionary 
Movement] Party, but of the historical and loyal MNR, not the 
MNR that lets its name be used so that the United States may 
govern our country through a gringo made in Bolivia. 
  This trial is totally ridiculous. It is a political and 
biased trial. Nothing was proved against me. The Bolivian 
state is overburdened with corruption, so much so that 
corruption has become the property of the Bolivian Government. 
Corrupt practices are rampant in the three branches of 
government -- the Executive, the Legislative Branch, and lower 
levels of the judiciary. Malfeasance and corruption are 
prevalent in the judiciary because there are no mechanisms in 
force to prevent this, such as better salaries and wages, or 
increasing the number of judges to prevent the backlog of work. 
[passage indistinct] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

